White Wine Quality Exploration by Archit Goel

This report explores the white wine quality dataset. The dataset consists details about chemical properties and a quality rating for 4898 wine samples.

Univariate Plots Section

## [1] 4898   13

The dataset consists of 4898 rows and 13 colummns. First column is the serial number for the wine samples, followed by 11 columns of various chemical properties and the last column contains the quality rating for the wine sample.

We may want to recode quality into a categorical variables, and consider recoding the current values into quality buckets such as low, below average, average, above average, and high quality.

Quality ratings are majorly concentrated between 5 to 7 (inclusive) and all quality ratings are between 3 to 9 (inclusive). For further analysis, quality will be recoded into three buckets - Below average (3,4,5), Average (6), Above average (7,8,9)

Variables associated with acidity (i.e.fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid) have a slight positively skewed distribution, with considerable outliers. If the outliers were ignored, then they have a normal distribution

Residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide have a positively skewed distribution with outliers mostly on the higher side of their value range

Density, pH, and sulphates too have some outliers mostly on the larger side Alcohol has an irregular distribution/ shape

Recode quality into a categorical variable per above decided buckets and name it quality_cat

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Our dataset has 4898 observations (rows) and 13 variables (columns). We have created an extra variable which is recoded from the quality rating variable

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest for us is the quality rating of wine samples and we will try to understand which factors affect the quality ratings of the wine

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Other than quality, it would be interesting to focus on alcohol content and how quality is dependent on the alcohol quantity of the wine. Also it would be interesting to explore other wine properties such as density, residual sugar, and sulphur dioxide content to notice any patterns

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Originally quality was a discrete variable, which we recoded for further analysis and converted it into a categorical variable. The new recoded vairable for quality (i.e. quality_cat) has 3 values: Below average (rating of 3,4,5), average (rating of 6), and above average (rating of 7,8,9)

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the
form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The scale for most of the variables histogram was adjusted to report a tidier form of presentation. Quality was recoded for further analysis.

Bivariate Plots Section

Bivariate Analysis

From the correlation coefficients between all variables we can observe that majoirty of the pairs of variables have a weak correlation (i.e.smaller than 0.3) and some pairs have a moderate correlation (i.e.between 0.3 and 0.7), while only 2 pairs have a strong correlation (i.e.greater than 0.7)

We would like to further explore the relation for below variable pairs: - quality and alcohol - quality and density - alcohol and density - free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide - density and residual sugar - density and total sulfur dioxide - alcohol and residual sugar - alcohol and total sulfur dioxide

From the above chart we can easily interpret a relation between alcohol quantity and the wine quality rating. Wines that are rated high in quality tend to have a higher alcohol content

From the above chart we can interpret that wines that are rated higher in quality tend to have a lower density

A strong negative correlation can be observed between acohol content and density of the wine

A strong positive relation between free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide. This relation seems logical considering free sulfur dioxide is a subset of total sulfur dioxide.

There is a strong positive correlation between residual sugar and density of the wine

There exists a moderate positive correlation between density of the wine and the total sulfur dioxide content of the wine

The relation between alcohol quantity and residual sugar content of the wine is a weak negative relation. We would discontinue the analysis for this pair

Alcohol and total sulfiur dioxide have a weak negative relation

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

The main feature of our analysis, quality of the wine has a strong relationship with alcohol content and density of the wine. Quality has a positive relation with the quantity of alcohol in the wine, and a negative relation with the density of the wine.

As expected alcohol and density had a high negative relation

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Other features, such as, residual sugar and total sulfur dioxide were positively related with the density of the wine, and therefore had an indirect negative impact on the quality of the wine

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relation in our dataset was between residual sugar in the wine and density of the wine. This was a positive relation with a correlation factor of 0.84 This is relation looks logical as a higher amount of residuals in any liquid would tend to increase the density of that liquid

Multivariate Plots Section

Majority of our sample wines with Above average quality (i.e.wines with quality rating 7, 8, or 9) fall in the bottom right quadrant with low density and high alcohol content

From the above two charts we can report that a wine sample with above average quality is more likely to have a low density and low residual sugar

We can also abserve that some wine samples have a below average quality rating even though they have low residual sugar content. This indicates that having a low density is a more important parameter of an above average wine

There is high variance in the above two plots. However, we can observe that majority of the above average wines have a lower total sulfur dioxide (less than 150ppm) quantity and an average free sulfur dioxide quantity (~ 20-45 ppm)

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

From our multivariate analysis, we can report that the wines with above average quality seem to have a combination of low density and high alcohol content, and it is preferable that the wines have low residual sugar

It was evident that low density could be prioritised over low residual sugar. But having said that, low residual sugar is an important criteria for an above average wine quality too

From our analysis, we can say that above average quality wines seem to have a low free sulfur dioxide content (~ 20-45 ppm)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

From our bivariate analysis, we knew that density and residual sugar are highly positively correlated with each other. While wine quality was negatively correlated with the density. Which led us to assume that low residual sugar will indirectly be related with good quality wines. However, from our multivariate analysis we can observe that some below average wines also have a low residual sugar, hence, indicating that having a low density is a more important parameter of an above average wine sample

Plot Two

Description Two

Density and alcohol have the strongest relation with quality of the wine. While density has a negative co-relation with wine quality, alcohol quantity has a positive co-relation with wine quality We can observe that majority of the wine sample with an Above average quality rating (i.e.a rating of 7, 8, or 9) fall in the bottom right quadrant of the plot, indicating that good quality wines have a low density and high alcohol content

Plot Three

Description Three

Density and residual sugar had the strongest co-relation in our analysis. The pair has a co-relation factor of 0.84, which is a strong positive relation. The above plot consists of a distribution of wine quality by density and residual sugar. We can observe from the plot that majority of the Above Average wines have a low density and low residual sugar An interesting point in the plot is that a considerable number of Below Average wines also have low residual sugar but a high density. This indicates that having a low density is a comparatively more important parameter of an above average wine

Reflection

We began with understanding the basic distribution of all the variables in our dataset. This helped in noting one limitation of the dataset, i.e.lack of sample with extreme quality ratings. It was noted that majority of the sample has a quality rating of 5, 6, and 7 with very little sample with other quality ratings and no sample with 1, 2, and 10. For further analysis a new variable was created for quality which had quality ratings divided into three buckets

A correlation matrix between all variables helped us in finding the variable pairs which had a considerable co-relation and were of interest. Our main priority in this step was to identify the primary variables which were highly related with quality of wine. We also explored variables which had a strong/ moderate relation with these primary variables

Alcohol content and density were two variables which have a comparatively high relation with quality of wine. Density has a negative co-relation with wine quality, alcohol quantity has a positive co-relation with wine quality. Density and residual sugar had the strongest co-relation. Majority of the high quality wines had a low total sulfur dioxide (less than 150ppm) quantity and low free sulfur dioxide quantity (~ 20-45 ppm)

However, it must be noted that all the insights are limited by the dataset. One of the limitations of our analysis is that the data was collected from one particular area in Portugal. Also, it does not contain any sample with extreme quality ratings, and a low sample size for very low and very high quality ratings.

An interesting aspect could be to build a predictive model for wine quality based on the chemical properties in the dataset. It would also be interesting to factor in the price of the wine sample, and explore how the price varies/ depends on the various chemical properties of the wine
